\begin_layout Section
Classical theories
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Capital structure is an old topic and I feel really boring whenever I have
 to visit this old friend.
 There are several pillars in this 
\emph on
financing decision
\emph default
: tradeoff theory, pecking order theory, and market timing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Pecking order theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "shyam-sunder1999testing"

\end_inset

 propose two models to test pecking order theory and static tradeoff theory.
 For pecking order theory, they use the deficit and change in debt relation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta D_{it}=a+b_{PO}DEF_{it}+e_{it}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $DEF=DIV+X+\Delta W+R-C$
\end_inset

, where DIV is dividend payment, X is capital expenditure, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta W$
\end_inset

 is change in working capital, R is current portion of long-term debt at
 start of period, and C is operating cash flow.
 Deficit is the financial deficit of firms that inflow cash is not sufficient
 to pay for outflow cash.
 The pecking order theory predicts that 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{PO}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For static tradeoff theory, the regression is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta D_{it}=a+b_{TA}\left(D_{it}^{*}-D_{it-1}\right)+e_{it}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{*}$
\end_inset

is target debt ratio which is historical average of debt ratio.
 Firms should adjust to the target debt ratio, so tradeoff theory predicts
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{TA}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results support the pecking order theory.
 The pecking order theory also has higher power test, because it can reject
 the simulated data from the tradeoff theory, but tradeoff theory fails
 to reject the simulated data from pecking order theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Market timing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "baker2002markettiming"

\end_inset

 write one of the most influential paper about capital structure.
 They find that market timing affects firm leverage and the effect is persistent
 and lasts up to 10 years (market overvaluation in previous 10 years affect
 leverage now!!!).
 Thus, current capital structure is a cumulative result of past attempts
 to time the market.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The smartest thing in this paper is 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "baker2002markettiming"

\end_inset

 find a new measure to distinguish between M/B (that could proxy for growth
 opportunity) and external-financing weighted average M/B ratio (to proxy
 for market timing attempt).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{M}{B}\right)_{efwa,t-1}=\sum_{s=0}^{t-1}\frac{e_{s}+d_{s}}{\sum_{r=0}^{t-1}e_{r}+d_{r}}.\left(\frac{M}{B}\right)_{s}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notes that they drop 
\begin_inset Formula $M/B>10$
\end_inset

 and if 
\begin_inset Formula $weight<0$
\end_inset

 (when net issue <0), they set 
\begin_inset Formula $weight=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This variable takes high values for firms that raised external finance when
 the M/B ratio was high and vice-versa.
 It captures two things in history: (1) overvaluation in history in M/B
 ratio and (2) debt and equity issue (in term of 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, which are net equity and net debt issued).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Their main model includes both current investment opportunities and past
 attempts of market timing:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{D}{A}\right)_{t}=a+b\left(\frac{M}{B}\right)_{efwa,t-1}+c\left(\frac{M}{B}\right)_{t-1}+d\left(\frac{PPE}{A}\right)_{t-1}+e\left(\frac{EBITDA}{A}\right)_{t-1}+f\, log(S)_{t-1}+u_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They always find a strong negative relation between leverage and their overvalua
tion timing attempts.
 In addition, the coefficient of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{M}{B}\right)_{t-1}$
\end_inset

 is less significant or even positive (high growth firms need more external
 finance) , which proves that their new measure perform better to capture
 the market timing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And the most interesting is the coeffcient of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{M}{B}\right)_{efwa,t-1}$
\end_inset

 is at its place for up to 10 years after IPO, a very persistent effect.
\end_layout

