\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The paper I want to discuss now is 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "lemmon2008backto"

\end_inset

.
 The most important finding is their Figure 1.
 This figure shows the future 20-year evolution of leverage for 4 portfolios
 constructed by 
\emph on
sorting firms based on their current leverage
\emph default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Each year, they sort firms into quartiles according to leverage ratios:
 Very High, High, Medium, and Low.
 The formation year is year 0.
 Then we hold the portfolio composition constant for subsequent 20 years.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Repeat these 2 steps for every year in the sample period (39 year so 39
 sets of event-time average).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compute average leverage of each portfolio across 39 sets within each event
 year: year 0 to year +20.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What do we see? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There is a 
\emph on
convergence tendency
\emph default
 in leverage to a moderate level (at middle).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Despite the convergence, the leverage ratios are 
\emph on
remarkably stable
\emph default
 because the difference between groups still statistically and economically
 significant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Explain: the presence of a 
\emph on
transitory (i.e., short-run component)
\emph default
 that leads to a gradual convergence in leverage ratios, as well as a 
\emph on
permanent (i.e., long-run component)
\emph default
 that leads to highly persistent cross-sectional differences in leverage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Another property is adjusted R2 from traditional leverage regressions ranges
 from 18% to 29%, while the adjusted R2 of firm fixed effect is 60%, meaning
 that majority of variation in leverage is unexplained by previously identified
 determinants.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In addition, the coefficients of previously identified determinants of leverage
 decrease in magnitude of 65%-85% on average after controlling for firm
 fixed effects and serially correlated errors.
 From this finding, later studies in corporate structure tend to use firm
 fixed effect and serial correlated errors in the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Thus, they suggest that existing determinants of capital strucutre appear
 to explain a relatively small fraction of the variation in leverage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another important implication of their finding is firms tend to rebalance
 capital structure toward a largely 
\emph on
time-invariant target
\emph default
 (i.e., unobserved permanent component of leverage) rather than a time-varying
 target specification as in some other studies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
The role of initial leverage
\series default
: 
\begin_inset Formula $Leverage_{it}=(+)Leverage_{i0}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Leverage_{i0}$
\end_inset

 is first nonmissing value for leverage in data.
 The coefficient is positive and t-stat is large (>28).
 
\emph on
Initial leverage
\emph default
 is the single most important determinant of future capital structure in
 the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Variance decomposition
\series default
: the idea of variance decomposition is to see how much the sum of squares
 of the model could be explained by the factors in the model (such as firm
 FE, year FE, firm characteristics).
 The results show that most of the effect is from the firm fixed effect,
 not year fixed effect and firm characteristics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
First, the results show that leverage contains an important 
\emph on
unobserved firm-specific component
\emph default
 that is not fully captured by existing determinants.
 In other words, controlling for previously identified determinants does
 not alleviate the concern over heterogeneous intercepts, a result with
 potentially important implications for empirical studies that we elaborate
 below.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Second, the variance decomposition reinforces the finding that the 
\emph on
majority of the total variation in leverage is due to cross-sectional difference
s
\emph default
, as opposed to time-series variation.
\end_layout

